ors, and calling for reinforced international coordination (for example, in the treatment of distressed banks), the authors put forth a number of principles to deal with issues regarding the economic incentives of financial institutions, the impact of economic shocks, and the role of political constraints. Offering a global perspective, Balancing the Banks should be read by anyone concerned with solving the current crisis and preventing another such calamity in the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBUSINESS &ampxECONOMICSvBanks &ampxBanking. 0aBanks and bankingvGovernment policy. 0aBanks and bankingvState supervision. 0aBanks and bankingxGovernment policy. 0aBanks and bankingxState supervision. 0aFinancial crisesxHistoryv21st century. 0aFinancial crisesxHistoryy21st century. 0aGlobal Financial Crisis, 2008-2009. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Banks & Banking.2bisacsh  aBasel Accords.  aG20 countries.  abanking industry.  abanking regulation.  abanking sector.  acapital requirements.  acredit-rating agency.  adistressed banks.  aeconomy.  afinancial crises.  afinancial crisis.  afinancial industry.  afinancial innovation.  afinancial institution.  afinancial policy.  afinancial regulation.  afinancial system reform.  aglobal finance.  ainternational cooperation.  ainternational financial regime.  aprudential regulation.  areal estate lending.  aregulatory reform.  astate aid.  asubsidies.1 aDewatripont, Mathias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRochet, Jean-Charles, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aRochet, Jean-Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTirole, Jean, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aTirole, Jean, eco